# SolarTracker Core Architecture

- The solution must follow a strict layered architecture.
- Prefer domain-driven design when it improves the model and the additional abstraction overhead remains acceptable.
- `SolarTracker.Domain` must not depend on any other project.
- `SolarTracker.Application` may depend only on `SolarTracker.Domain`, except for `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Abstractions` when using framework logging abstractions.
- `SolarTracker.Infrastructure` may depend only on `SolarTracker.Application` and `SolarTracker.Domain`.
- `SolarTracker.Api` should stay transport-first and must not contain persistence logic.
- Reusable business orchestration belongs in `SolarTracker.Application` or `SolarTracker.Domain`; localized endpoint-specific read composition is acceptable when it remains narrow and transport-facing.
- `SolarTracker.IoC` is the composition root and owns the registration of concrete implementations.

# Dependency Rules

- Do not bypass layer boundaries.
- Place real business rules and domain behavior on domain entities or value objects when that keeps the design clearer and more cohesive.
- Do not force DDD patterns when the extra indirection, types, or orchestration cost is disproportionate to the benefit.
- Do not access Entity Framework types outside `SolarTracker.Infrastructure`.
- Do not place HTTP, GPIO, OpenAPI, or serialization concerns in `Domain` or `Application`.
- In `SolarTracker.Application`, allow only logging abstractions and source-generated logging methods from `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging`; do not introduce other infrastructure concerns there.
- Do not introduce mediator, event bus, or message-driven indirection unless a dedicated rule explicitly requires it.

# Composition Rules

- Primary Constructor injection is preferable over old-school Consturctor injection.
- If a constructor-injected dependency is not used, remove it from the constructor instead of keeping an unused injection.
- Property injection and method injection are not allowed.
- Avoid service locator patterns, except when a hosted service creates a scope to resolve scoped dependencies for a single background work item.
- Keep `Program.cs` minimal and delegate endpoint registration to extension methods.
